    "title": "Indian banks may take more than $3 bln hit from PNB fraud - tax dept",
    "locations": [],
    "highlightText": "",
    "language": "english",
    "persons": [],
    "text": "NEW DELHI, Feb 17 (Reuters) - Indian banks could take a hit of at least $2.7 billion from loans and corporate guarantees provided to Punjab National Bank in a $1.77 billion fraud case, the tax department said on Saturday.\nAs of March 2017, banks had extended loans and guarantees worth 176.32 billion rupees ($2.74 billion) to companies tied to billionaire jeweller Nirav Modi and his uncle Mehul Choksi, the tax department said in a note seen by Reuters.\nBut the total hit to Indian banks “may well exceed” that amount the department said in its note.\n$1 = 64.2400 Indian rupees Reporting by Sanjeev Miglani; Editing by Rafael Nam\n ",
